@mboehm7 Can you take a look at this approach to adding implicit bounds at the parser level to **PyDML**?  Essentially, I insert a `1` int expression for implicit lower bounds, and `nrow(X)` or `ncol(X)` for implicit upper bounds.

If we think this is a decent approach, I can clean this up and add tests.

Note: We will only apply this to PyDML.

Thank you @nishi-t. I tried it out and it works great. This is a very useful contribution!

@dusenberrymw That is a great suggestion (to add some short tests for this). @nishi-t, in case it helps, for a script like:

```
def ifTest(x: int):
    if (x == 1):
       print('A')

z = ifTest(1)
```

you can set the expected output in the Java test using something like:

```
setExpectedStdOut("A");
```

@niketanpansare Overall, this is awesome!   I created new layers in my library using the new built-in functions internally for convolution and max pooling, and plugged them into all my DML test suites.  The convolution functions work great!  

I did find one problem with the built-in max pooling function: values are always compared to a lower-bounded threshold of `0`, so if a patch has all negative values, the output for the max pooling operation over that patch will be `0`, rather than the maximum negative number in that patch.  I will comment on the line, but a quick update fixes it.  Would probably be good to add a few tests over entirely negative tensors to unit test it.

Looking forward to the GPU & Spark implementations!

Good catch!  It looks like the issue is the individual test classes are using same directory:
private final static String TEST_CLASS_DIR = TEST_DIR + Conv2DTest.class.getSimpleName() + "/";
I can update the class name.

